    {
      "id": "ed6a95549cbe7a797a79a7c6c6b49aa7d3d8b699",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-02 00:36:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nBob, it is probably possible to get the OBD device name from the mdd_device struct in that function. I'm just on my phone, so cannot check, but I'd suspect that there is a simple helper function to do this already - check other CERROR() calls in the MDD code that print the device name already. \n\nSecondly, I'm confused why you drop the lock before the \"if (rc != 0)\" case, instead of inside?  It is guaranteed that if the lock is still held at that point that rc must be non-zero, and the whole goal of that change was to hold the lock until the cleanup could be done, so no other user sees it in the intermediate state.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
